{
  "answer": "**The passage is from Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, chapter 20 (\"Shikwa,\" meaning \"The Complaint\"), a long verse poem in which the Muslim community laments to God about its past glories and present decline.[^1]**\n\nThe matching stanza—a single rhetorical stretch of six rhymed questions—is:\n\n> You tell us then, who was it that tore out Khyber’s mighty door?  \n> Who was it that laid Caesar’s city flat upon the floor?  \n> Who smashed the man-made idols of the gods that men adore?  \n> And who was it that cut to shreds the armies of the war?  \n> Who was it that extinguished Zoroaster’s sacred fire?  \n> And who revived the memory of God, our one desire?[^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 20 \"Shikwa,\" [chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-ec4443).",
